Shiny: An Introduction

Introduction

Shiny is an R package for building interactive web applications. It allows you to combine the computational power of R with the interactivity of the web.

Shiny apps are

  • easy to write (no web development skills required) and
  • easy to deploy.

Resources:

  • Shiny Cheat Sheet
  • Shiny Gallery (a showcase of a variety of applications built with Shiny, with source code)
  • Teach Yourself Shiny (tutorial)
  • Mastering Shiny (book)
  • Shiny Developer Conference (the first two videos on Effective Reactive Programming by Joe Cheng are particularly good)

Creating a Shiny App

RStudio makes it simple to create the template for a Shiny App:

  1. File → New File → Shiny Web App.

  1. Choose a suitable name for the app.
  2. Select either “Single File” or “Multiple File” app.
  3. Select a directory in which to create the app.
  4. Press Create.

You can immediately run the resulting template app by pressing Run App.

Example: Country Populations

The set of examples can be found in the country-populations folder.

Let’s deconstruct the app. Every app has two components:

  1. a user interface (UI) which describes the app’s appearance and
  2. a server which is where the functionality of the app is implemented.

We’ll start with the UI, which uses a fluidPage() page layout. This applies the Bootstrap principle of dividing the page into rows, which in turn are broken down into columns.

ui <- fluidPage(
    titlePanel("Population Explosion"),
    sidebarLayout(
        sidebarPanel(
            selectInput(
                inputId = "country",
                label = "Country",
                choices = country,
                selected = "ZAF"
            )
        ),
        mainPanel(
            plotOutput("plot")
        )
    )
)
  • The page is divided into two panels, “side-bar” and “main”, using sidebarLayout(). These two panels are populated in turn by sidebarPanel() and mainPanel().
  • Although this is not necessarily the case, input elements are usually found in the side-bar panel while output elements are located in the main panel.
  • There’s a selectInput() input selector in the side-bar panel and a plotOutput() display function in the main panel.

  • The server generates the plot in response to changes in the country selector.
  • The value of the country selector is retrieved as input$country.
  • The name country comes from the inputId of the input selector.
  • This is used to filter out only the corresponding records from the data.
  • These data are then used to generate a plot. The plot is returned by the renderPlot() function and assigned to output$plot.
  • The name plot is used to refer to this output in the UI (it’s the argument to plotOutput()).
server <- function(input, output) {
    output$plot <- renderPlot({
        data <- populations %>% filter(code == input$country)
        ggplot(data, aes(x = year, y = population)) + geom_point()
    })
}

Finally the app is launched by a call to shinyApp(), which consumes both the UI and server.

shinyApp(ui = ui, server = server)

Shiny App File Layout

You can create either a “Single File” or “Multiple File” app:

  • a Single File app has just one file, app.R, which contains both the server and UI code, but
  • a Multiple File has two files, ui.R and server.R, which each contain the respective components of the app.

Sharing Apps

shinyapps.io provides a simple platform for sharing apps.

  1. Go to https://www.shinyapps.io/. Press the Dashboard button.
  2. Log in (create an account if you don’t yet have one).
  3. Open the script for a Shiny app.
  4. Press the Publish button (blue symbol in top right corner).
  5. If there are multiple files listed, check only the ones relevant to the app (this includes data files!).
  6. Choose an appropriate Title for the app.
  7. Press the Publish button.

During the deploy process a rsconnect/ folder will be created. Don’t delete this: it will make future deployments faster and easier.

UI

There is great flexibility in how you lay out the interface of a Shiny application. If you are feeling particularly hard core then you can actually just code the interface in native HTML. But why punish yourself? Instead take advantage of the functionality which is built into the shiny package which will allow you to easily set up an attractive interface.

There are three classes of function which are used for building the interface:

  • Layout — high level functions which dictate the overall layout of the elements in the application;
  • Input — functions for taking application input (for example, text, checkboxes, radio buttons and dates); and
  • Output — functions for displaying output from the server (for example, text, HTML, tables and plots).

Input

There’s a huge range of input widgets available:

  • actionButton()
  • actionLink()
  • checkboxInput() and checkboxGroupInput()
  • dateInput() and dateRangeInput()
  • fileInput()
  • numericInput()
  • passwordInput()
  • radioButtons()
  • selectInput()
  • slideInput()
  • submitButton() and
  • textInput().

Take a look at the widget gallery to see each of these in action.

Every input component has a unique input ID. This is how the values are referenced from the server.

Server

The server implements a single function with two parameters, input and output:

  • The input parameter is used to reference values from the input elements in the UI.
  • The output parameter is used to pass elements back to the UI for display.

Output

The following rendering functions are used in the server to generate output:

  • renderPlot() – a static plot
  • renderPlotly() – an interactive plot (implemented in {plotly})
  • renderLeaflet() – an interactive map (implemented in {leaflet})
  • renderTable() – a static table
  • renderDataTable() – an interactive table (implemented in {DT})
  • renderText()
  • renderPrint() – captures printed output
  • renderImage() and
  • renderUI() – arbitrary UI components.

Associated with each of these is a corresponding output function which is used to display the rendered content in the UI.

  • plotOutput()
  • plotlyOutput()
  • leafletOutput()
  • tableOutput()
  • dataTableOutput()
  • textOutput()
  • verbatimTextOutput()
  • imageOutput() and
  • uiOutput() or htmlOutput().

A graphical representation of how some of the functions work together:



This is how it works:

  • The rendering function is used to generate output, which is then assigned to a named component of output.
  • This is then displayed by the corresponding output function in the UI, referring to it by its component name in output.

Reactivity

An R script normally runs from “top to bottom”. A Shiny app, however, is quite different. Once shinyApp() is called, the app enters an event loop, in which it responds to “events” arising from the UI. This is known as “reactivity”. Events are propagated from the UI to the server via input and results flow in the opposite direction via output.

Reactivity is key to an effective Shiny application. Data needs to flow smoothly from the UI’s input elements to the server. The output generated by the server needs to be effectively displayed in the UI. When input elements change, the corresponding output elements should respond immediately.

In this section we are going to dig into how reactivity works.

Whenever an input widget is modified the value of the corresponding component in input changes.

When the app is in the above state, the components of input have the following values:

> input$country
[1] "ZAF" "DNK" "CUB"
input$size
[1] 1
input$line
[1] FALSE
input$show_table
[1] TRUE

When a component in input changes the states of all of the output components that reference it become invalidated and must be recalculated. This is the core of reactivity!

So, for example, in the render function below if either the country, line or size components of input change then the plot will be regenerated. However, since the render function does not depend on the show_table component of input, changes to this component will not trigger regeneration of the plot.

    output$plot <- renderPlotly({
        data <- populations %>% filter(code %in% input$country)
        p <- ggplot(data, aes(x = year, y = population / 1000000)) +
            scale_y_log10("Population (million)") +
            theme(legend.title = element_blank())
        if (input$line) p <- p + geom_line(aes(group = code))
        p + geom_point(aes(color = code), size = input$size)
    })
    output$table <- renderDataTable({
        if (input$show_table) {
